docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg was admitted to Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore on Friday night after experiencing chills and fever earlier in the day, a Supreme Court spokeswoman said on Saturday.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Friday blocked rulings from federal courts in Ohio and Michigan that had struck down voting maps in those states as unconstitutional partisan gerrymanders. Both courts had found that Republican legislators had violated the Constitution by drawing voting districts to hurt the electoral chances of Democratic candidates.

headline.main: Supreme Court Blocks Two Rulings Striking Down Voting Maps
headline.print_headline: Court Blocks Two Decisions That Rejected Voting Maps, Setting Stage for a Wider Ruling

docs.abstract: The court has ruled that racial gerrymanders can violate the Constitution, but it has struggled with voting maps warped by politics.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Thursday ruled that federal courts are powerless to hear challenges to partisan gerrymandering, the practice in which the party that controls the state legislature draws voting maps to help elect its candidates.

headline.main: Supreme Court Bars Challenges to Partisan Gerrymandering

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Chief Justice John G. Roberts Jr. has sat in the center seat on the Supreme Court bench since his arrival in 2005. But only this term did he assume true leadership of the court.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump asked the Supreme Court on Friday to shield his financial records from disclosure to investigators for the second time in two days. His latest request was an emergency application that asked the court to temporarily block the release of records held by his accounting firm to a House committee while the justices consider whether to hear his appeal.

headline.main: Trump Again Asks Supreme Court to Block Release of His Financial Records
headline.print_headline: Trump Again Asks Top Court to Block Release of His Financial Records

docs.abstract: Mick Mulvaney, the president’s acting chief of staff, and John R. Bolton, his former national security adviser, clashed in court even as more accounts of internal schisms emerged in books and testimony.
docs.snippet: Mick Mulvaney, the president’s acting chief of staff, and John R. Bolton, his former national security adviser, clashed in court even as more accounts of internal schisms emerged in books and testimony.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s chief of staff and former national security adviser clashed in court on Monday. Two new books describe how top aides to the president secretly plotted to circumvent him. And nearly every day brings more testimony about the deep internal schism over the president’s effort to pressure Ukraine for domestic political help.

headline.main: Feud Between Trump Advisers Underscores a White House Torn by Rivalries
headline.print_headline: Feud Between Trump Aides Underscores Rivalries in White House
